  <entry xml:base="http://pauleveritt.github.io/blog/atom.xml">
    <title type="text">Using Docker in PyCharm</title>
    <id>http://pauleveritt.github.io/posts/docker_intro/</id>
    <updated>2015-12-08T00:00:00Z</updated>
    <published>2015-12-08T00:00:00Z</published>
    <link href="http://pauleveritt.github.io/posts/docker_intro/" />
    <author>
      <name>Paul Everitt</name>
    </author>
    <content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Modern development workflows emphasize isolation and reproducability
in development and production. &lt;a class=&quot;reference external&quot; href=&quot;https://www.docker.com&quot;&gt;Docker&lt;/a&gt; and
its platform approach to containers has become very popular. With
PyCharm Professional Edition 5,
&lt;a class=&quot;reference external&quot; href=&quot;http://blog.jetbrains.com/pycharm/2015/10/announcing-pycharm-5-eap-143-165-docker-integration/&quot;&gt;Docker is now supported&lt;/a&gt;
as a remote interpreter.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
